{"title_page": "French occupation zone in Germany", "text_new": "{{Expand French|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''[[France|French]] occupation zone''' (in [[German language|German]]: ''Franz\u00f6sische Besatzungszone''), was one of the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied areas]] established in [[Germany]] after [[World War II]].\n\nFollowing the [[Armistice of the First World War]], [[Allies of the First World War |Allied]] forces occupied part of German territory until the [[1920s]] and France administered the [[Territory of the Saar Basin]] until 1935.\n\nThe strength of the occupying forces was 100,000 in the Rhine territories in the calmest periods. The maximum of soldiers was reached in May 1921 during the first occupation of [[Ruhrort]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]] with {{formatnum: 250000}} soldiers including {{formatnum: 210000}} French.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}[http://rha.revues.org/index6333.html Occupy Germany after 1918], ''[[Historical review of the armies]],'' 2009.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAt the end of the [[Second World War]], before the [[Yalta conference]] (4-11 February 1945), no occupation zone in Germany was to be allocated to France. At the insistence of [[Charles de Gaulle]] and [[Provisional Government of the French Republic]], [[Winston Churchill | Churchill]] obtained from [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] that an occupation zone was to be allocated to France provided that this consists of zones previously occupied by the Americans and the British <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\">\n{{web link\n| url = http://docnum.univ-lorraine.fr/public/UPV-M/Theses/1994/Perrein_Engels.Helene.LMZ9412_1.pdf\n| format = Pdf\n| titre = The military presence in Germany from 1945 to 1993\n| author = H. Pennein-Engels\n| publisher = University of Metz - Faculty of Letters and Human Sciences\n| year = 1994\n| accessed on = July 8, 2015\n}}.</ref>:\n\n; Extract from the final press release, Article 4:\n{{block quote | IV. Occupation zone for France and control council in Germany <br />\nIt was decided that an area of \u200b\u200bGermany would be allocated to France to be occupied by French forces. This zone would be taken from the British and American zones and its extent would be fixed by the British and the Americans, in agreement with the French Provisional Government.\n\nIt was also decided that the French Provisional Government would be invited to be part of the [[Allied Control Council|Allied Control Commission]] in Germany.}}\n\nThis is how the British ceded the [[Saarland(Land)|Saarland]], the [[Rhineland Palatinate|Palatinate]] and the territories on the left bank of the [[Rhine]] until [[Remagen]] including [[Trier (Germany) | Trier]], [[Koblenz]] and [[Montabaur]]. While the Americans ceded the South of [[Baden Baden]] (which became [[Baden (Land) | Land of Baden]])), the South of [[People's Free State of W\u00fcrttemberg]] (which became Land of [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]]), [[District of Lindau | Lindau circle]] on [[Lake Constance]] and four circles of [[Hesse (Land) | Hesse]] on the shore right of the Rhine <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />.\n\n[[French forces in Germany]] officially took possession of their area on July 26, 1945.<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />\n\nIn April and May 1945, the [[1st Army (France)|French 1st Army]] had captured [[Karlsruhe]] and [[Stuttgart]], and conquered a territory extending to [[Berghof (residence)|Hitler's Eagle's Nest]] and the westernmost part of Austria. In July, the French relinquished Stuttgart to the Americans, and in exchange were given control over cities west of the Rhine such as [[Mainz]] and [[Koblenz]].<ref>{{cite book |last=de Gaulle|first= Charles|title= M\u00e9moires de guerre : Le Salut 1944-1946|year=1959 |publisher=Plon|pages=170, 207}}</ref> All this resulted in two barely contiguous areas of Germany along the French border which met at just a single point along the River [[Rhine]]. Three German states (''[[States of Germany|Land]]'') were established: [[Rheinland Pfalz]] in the North and West and on the other hand [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]] and [[South Baden]], who later formed [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] together with ''W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden'' of the American Zone.\n\nThe French Zone of Occupation included the [[Saar Protectorate]], which was disentangled from it on 16 February 1946. By 18 December 1946 customs controls were established between the Saar area and Allied-occupied Germany. The French zone ceded further areas adjacent to the Saar (in mid-1946, early 1947, and early 1949).{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIncluded in the French zone was the town of [[B\u00fcsingen am Hochrhein]], a German exclave separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of neutral [[Switzerland|Swiss]] territory. The Swiss government agreed to allow limited numbers of French troops to pass through its territory in order to maintain law and order in B\u00fcsingen.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIt was not until August 12, 1945, that two Berlin districts ([[Reinickendorf | Reinickendorf]] and [[Wedding | Wedding District]]) were assigned to them.<ref name = \"GMFB\">{{cite web| url=http://ekladata.com/HsfUaqdi31GzolZtcyCvSXKbYcs/GMFB.pdf| format = Pdf\n| title = French Military Government of Berlin| author =| publisher =| year =| access-date = July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Fotothek df pk 0000178 036.jpg|[[Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin|French forces]] in front of the [[Brandenburg Gate]] in Berlin, 1946\nFile:Insigne-Forces-Fran\u00e7aises-Berlin.jpg|Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin (French Forces in Berlin) insignia after 1949\n</gallery>\n\nAt the end of October 1946, the French Zone had a population of:\n* Rheinland Pfalz 2.7 million\n* Baden (South Baden) 1.2 million\n* W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern 1.05 million\n(The Saar Protectorate had a further 0.8 million.)<ref name=\"digizeitschriften.de\">[http://www.digizeitschriften.de/dms/img/?PID=PPN514402342_1952%7Clog10 \"I. Gebiet und Bev\u00f6lkerung\"]. [[Statistisches Bundesamt]]. Wiesbaden.</ref>\n\nA [[French Education Directorate in Germany]] was created immediately to allow schooling for children of military and civilian families.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Monnet plan]]\n* [[Allied-occupied Austria]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[:de:Corine Defrance|Corine Defrance]], ''La Politique culturelle de la France sur la rive gauche du Rhin'', 1945-1955, [[Presses universitaires de Strasbourg]], 1994.\n* ''Compte rendu du deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s de l'Organisation des fonctionnaires r\u00e9sistants en Allemagne'', H\u00f6llhof, 1949\n*Hillel, Marc, ''L'occupation fran\u00e7aise en Allemagne 1945-1949'', Balland, 1983.\n\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Germany]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Germany| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1945]]\n[[Category:French military occupations]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Germany relations]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|date=April 2020}}\nThe '''[[France|French]] occupation zone''' (in [[German]]: ''Franz\u00f6sische Besatzungszone''), was one of the [[Allied-occupied Germany|allied areas]] established in [[Germany]] after [[World War II]].\n\nFollowing the [[Armistice of the First World War]], [[Allies of the First World War |Allied]] forces occupied part of German territory until the [[1920s]] and France administered the [[Territory of the Saar Basin]] until 1935.\n\nThe strength of the occupying forces was 100,000 in the Rhine territories in the calmest periods. The maximum of soldiers was reached in May 1921 during the first occupation of [[Ruhrort]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] and [[Duisburg]] with {{formatnum: 250000}} soldiers including {{formatnum: 210000}} French.<ref>{{in lang|fr}}[http://rha.revues.org/index6333.html Occupy Germany after 1918], ''[[Historical review of the armies]],'' 2009.</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAt the end of the [[Second World War]], before the [[Yalta conference]] (4-11 February 1945), no occupation zone in Germany was to be allocated to France. At the insistence of [[Charles de Gaulle]] and [[Provisional Government of the French Republic]], [[Winston Churchill | Churchill]] obtained from [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt|Roosevelt]] and [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin]] that an occupation zone was to be allocated to France provided that this consists of zones previously occupied by the Americans and the British <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\">\n{{web link\n| url = http://docnum.univ-lorraine.fr/public/UPV-M/Theses/1994/Perrein_Engels.Helene.LMZ9412_1.pdf\n| format = Pdf\n| titre = The military presence in Germany from 1945 to 1993\n| author = H. Pennein-Engels\n| publisher = University of Metz - Faculty of Letters and Human Sciences\n| year = 1994\n| accessed on = July 8, 2015\n}}.</ref>:\n\n; Extract from the final press release, Article 4:\n{{block quote | IV. Occupation zone for France and control council in Germany <br />\nIt was decided that an area of \u200b\u200bGermany would be allocated to France to be occupied by French forces. This zone would be taken from the British and American zones and its extent would be fixed by the British and the Americans, in agreement with the French Provisional Government.\n\nIt was also decided that the French Provisional Government would be invited to be part of the [[Allied Control Council|Allied Control Commission]] in Germany.}}\n\nThis is how the British ceded the [[Saarland(Land)|Saarland]], the [[Rhineland Palatinate|Palatinate]] and the territories on the left bank of the [[Rhine]] until [[Remagen]] including [[Trier (Germany) | Trier]], [[Koblenz]] and [[Montabaur]]. While the Americans ceded the South of [[Baden Baden]] (which became [[Baden (Land) | Land of Baden]])), the South of [[People's Free State of W\u00fcrttemberg]] (which became Land of [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]]), [[District of Lindau | Lindau circle]] on [[Lake Constance]] and four circles of [[Hesse (Land) | Hesse]] on the shore right of the Rhine <ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />.\n\n[[French forces in Germany]] officially took possession of their area on July 26, 1945.<ref name = \"Pennein-Engels\" />\n\nIn April and May 1945, the [[1st Army (France)|French 1st Army]] had captured [[Karlsruhe]] and [[Stuttgart]], and conquered a territory extending to [[Berghof (residence)|Hitler's Eagle's Nest]] and the westernmost part of Austria. In July, the French relinquished Stuttgart to the Americans, and in exchange were given control over cities west of the Rhine such as [[Mainz]] and [[Koblenz]].<ref>{{cite book |last=de Gaulle|first= Charles|title= M\u00e9moires de guerre : Le Salut 1944-1946|year=1959 |publisher=Plon|pages=170, 207}}</ref> All this resulted in two barely contiguous areas of Germany along the French border which met at just a single point along the River [[Rhine]]. Three German states (''[[States of Germany|Land]]'') were established: [[Rheinland Pfalz]] in the North and West and on the other hand [[W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern]] and [[South Baden]], who later formed [[Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg]] together with ''W\u00fcrttemberg-Baden'' of the American Zone.\n\nThe French Zone of Occupation included the [[Saar Protectorate]], which was disentangled from it on 16 February 1946. By 18 December 1946 customs controls were established between the Saar area and Allied-occupied Germany. The French zone ceded further areas adjacent to the Saar (in mid-1946, early 1947, and early 1949).{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIncluded in the French zone was the town of [[B\u00fcsingen am Hochrhein]], a German exclave separated from the rest of the country by a narrow strip of neutral [[Switzerland|Swiss]] territory. The Swiss government agreed to allow limited numbers of French troops to pass through its territory in order to maintain law and order in B\u00fcsingen.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nIt was not until August 12, 1945, that two Berlin districts ([[Reinickendorf | Reinickendorf]] and [[Wedding | Wedding District]]) were assigned to them.<ref name = \"GMFB\">{{cite web| url=http://ekladata.com/HsfUaqdi31GzolZtcyCvSXKbYcs/GMFB.pdf| format = Pdf\n| title = French Military Government of Berlin| author =| publisher =| year =| access-date = July 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\">\nFile:Fotothek df pk 0000178 036.jpg|[[Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin|French forces]] in front of the [[Brandenburg Gate]] in Berlin, 1946\nFile:Insigne-Forces-Fran\u00e7aises-Berlin.jpg|Forces Fran\u00e7aises \u00e0 Berlin (French Forces in Berlin) insignia after 1949\n</gallery>\n\nAt the end of October 1946, the French Zone had a population of:\n* Rheinland Pfalz 2.7 million\n* Baden (South Baden) 1.2 million\n* W\u00fcrttemberg-Hohenzollern 1.05 million\n(The Saar Protectorate had a further 0.8 million.)<ref name=\"digizeitschriften.de\">[http://www.digizeitschriften.de/dms/img/?PID=PPN514402342_1952%7Clog10 \"I. Gebiet und Bev\u00f6lkerung\"]. [[Statistisches Bundesamt]]. Wiesbaden.</ref>\n\nA [[French Education Directorate in Germany]] was created immediately to allow schooling for children of military and civilian families.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Monnet plan]]\n* [[Allied-occupied Austria]]\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [[:de:Corine Defrance|Corine Defrance]], ''La Politique culturelle de la France sur la rive gauche du Rhin'', 1945-1955, [[Presses universitaires de Strasbourg]], 1994.\n* ''Compte rendu du deuxi\u00e8me Congr\u00e8s de l'Organisation des fonctionnaires r\u00e9sistants en Allemagne'', H\u00f6llhof, 1949\n*Hillel, Marc, ''L'occupation fran\u00e7aise en Allemagne 1945-1949'', Balland, 1983.\n\n[[Category:World War II occupied territories|Germany]]\n[[Category:Allied occupation of Germany| ]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1945]]\n[[Category:French military occupations]]\n[[Category:1945 establishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:1949 disestablishments in Germany]]\n[[Category:France\u2013Germany relations]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGerman(link changed toGerman language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_occupation_zone_in_Germany"}
{"title_page": "Rieko Yauchi", "text_new": "{{Expand Japanese|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox shogi professional\n|name             = Reiko Yauchi\n|native_name      = \u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50\n|maiden_name      = <!--Only applicable to female professionals who married after turning pro-->\n|image            = File:\u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50RiekoYauchi.jpg\n|image_size       =\n|caption          =  Yauchi in 2013\n|born             = {{birth date and age|1980|01|10|mf=yes}}\n|hometown         = [[Gy\u014dda]], [[Saitama Prefecture]]\n|nationality      = Japanese\n|pro_date         = {{event date and age|1993|04|01|1980|01|10}}\n|badge_no         = W-16\n|teacher          = {{ill|Shigeru Sekine|ja|\u95a2\u6839\u8302}}\n|teacher_rank     = 9-dan\n|lifetime_titles  =\n|title            =\n|rank             = Women's 5-[[dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]\n|no_titles        = 6\n|tournaments      = 2 \n|jsa              = 16\n|female           = yes\n|othersite        = {{twitter|riebuusan}}\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Rieko Yauchi'''|\u77e2\u5185 \u7406\u7d75\u5b50|Yauchi Rieko|born January 10, 1980}} is a Japanese [[Professional shogi player#Women's professionals|women's professional shogi player]] ranked 5-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|dan]]. She is a former Women's {{ill|Women's Meijin (shogi)|lt=Meijin|ja|\u5973\u6d41\u540d\u4eba\u6226 (\u5c06\u68cb)}}, {{ill|Women's \u014ci|lt=\u014ci|ja|\u5973\u6d41\u738b\u4f4d\u6226}} and {{ill|Jo-\u014c|ja|\u30de\u30a4\u30ca\u30d3\u5973\u5b50\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3}} title holder.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/lady/16.html|script-title=ja:\u5973\u6d41\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50|title=Jory\u016b Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Yauchi Reiko|language=ja|trans-title=Women's Professional Shogi Player Database: Reiko Yauchi|publisher=[[Japan Shogi Association]]|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion history==\nYauchi's promotion history is as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/lady/16.html#jsTabE04_02|script-title=ja:\u5973\u6d41\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50 \u6607\u6bb5\u5c65\u6b74|title=Jory\u016b Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Yauchi Rieko Sh\u014ddan Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Women's Professional Shogi Player Database: Rieko Yauchi Promotion History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*1990: [[Professional shogi player#JSA|Women's Professional Apprentice League]]\n*1993, April 1: 2-[[Dan (rank)#Modern usage in shogi|ky\u016b]]\n*1995, April 1: 1-ky\u016b\n*1995, July 10: 1-dan\n*1997, April 1: 2-dan\n*1997, October 27: 3-dan\n*2004, August 3: 4-dan\n*2014, February 21: 5-dan\n\nNote: All ranks are [[Professional shogi player#Women's professionals|women's professional ranks]].\n\n==Titles and other championships==\nYauchi has appeared in major title matches eighteen times and has won a total of six titles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/lady/16.html#anc01|script-title=ja:\u5973\u6d41\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50 \u30bf\u30a4\u30c8\u30eb\u5c65\u6b74|title=Jory\u016b Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Yauchi Rieko Taitoru Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Women's Professional Shogi Player Database: Rieko Yauchi Major Title History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> In addition to major titles, Yauchi has won two other shogi championships.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shogi.or.jp/player/lady/16.html#anc02|script-title=ja:\u5973\u6d41\u68cb\u58eb\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9: \u77e2\u5185\u7406\u7d75\u5b50 \u512a\u52dd\u5c65\u6b74|title=Jory\u016b Kishi D\u0113tab\u0113su: Yauchi Rieko Y\u016bsh\u014d Rireki|language=ja|trans-title=Women's Professional Shogi Player Database: Rieko Yauchi Championship History|publisher=Japan Shogi Association|access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Major titles===\n{