i]]\n[[Category:Queen (shogi)]]\n\n{{Shogi-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MathXplore", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rieko_Yauchi"}
{"title_page": "Petites Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry", "text_new": "{{Infobox artwork\n | title             = Les Petites Heures de Jean de Berry\n | italic title      = no\n | image             = Jacquemart de Hesdin 002.jpg\n | image_size        = 250px\n | caption           = ''The Annunciation'',<br> miniature by [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]]<br>and [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]]\n | alt               =\n | artist            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]]\n* [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]]\n* [[Pseudo-Jacquemart]]\n* [[Master of the Trinity]]\n* [[Limbourg brothers]]\n}}\n | year              = 1375\u20131390\n | medium            = Illuminated [[book of hours]]\n | height_metric     = 21.5\n | width_metric      = 14.5\n | museum            = [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]\n | city              = Paris, France\n | catalogue         = Ms. Lat.18014\n}}\nThe '''Petites Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry''' is an illuminated [[book of hours]] commissioned by [[John, Duke of Berry]] between 1375 and 1385\u201390. It is known for its ornate [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature]] leaves and border decorations.\n\nSeveral artists were employed in the production. It was completed in two separate stages, each with a distinctive style. The earlier leaves were painted by artists influenced by [[Jean Pucelle]], the later by artists working in the vanguard of the [[International Gothic]] period of Gothic art. Because of this, the ''Petites Heures'' exemplifies the \"rupture in style\" that occurred in French illumination in the final two decades of the fourteenth century.<ref>[http://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc784809 Latin 18014] archivesetmanuscrits.bnf</ref>\n\nA high-resolution facsimile was published in 1988, with monographs by Avril, Dunlop and [[William Brunsdon Yapp|Yapp]].<ref>Husband, p. 45</ref>\n\n== History ==\nJean de Berry commissioned six books of hours between 1375 and 1416. The first, the ''Petites Heures'',<ref>Husband, pp. 24\u201325</ref> contains 182 miniatures. Work started c. 1375 but was interrupted in 1380 and the book was not completed until 1385\u201390.<ref>Husband, p.43</ref> It is now housed at the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] under the reference ms. lat. 18014.<ref>Husband, p. 25</ref>\n\nThe [[limner]] [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]], a pupil of Jean Pucelle, started work on the illuminations.<ref>Hourihane, p. 472</ref> By the time of his death in 1380, only nine miniatures had been completed.{{efn|Meiss and Avril attribute to Jean Le Noir the miniatures of folios 53, 76r, 79v, 82, 83v, 86v, 89v, 92v and 94v, as well as the figures of the angel Gabriel and the Virgin of the Annunciation (f.22) and those of the beggar and his children in the left margin of the 97v. Le Noir's hand can also be seen in the decorative plantlife and the delicate design of the filigree initials. He probably worked on 40v (Announcement to the Shepherds), 207 (Birth of John the Baptist), 208 (John the Baptist in the Wilderness), 212v (Dance of Salome)}} In 1384 the duke engaged [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]];<ref>Hourihane, p. 453</ref> completion of the book was left to him{{efn|Jacquemart de Hesdin's hand is seen in folios 8, 38, 40v, 42v, 45v, 203, 212, 214}} and an assistant known as the Master of the Trinity,{{efn|Named for his contributions to Hours of the Trinity, he executed five of that offices' eight miniatures: ff. 183, 188, 189, 192, 194v. His hand is recognized in the painting of the Coronation of the Virgin, in four paintings of the office of the Holy Ghost, and Lamentations (158, 163). Also in the series of offices of the week (137v, 140v, 141v) and in some paintings depicting prayers (100v, 103v, 196, 198v). Meiss also sees his hand in the great paintings of the office of John the Baptist: f. 203, 209v, 211, 214.}} and to another artist known as [[Pseudo-Jacquemart]], who painted in some of the underdrawings left by Jean le Noir, as well as contributing his own compositions.{{efn|In addition to the calendar, Pseudo-Jacquemart completed the scenes begun by Jean Le Noir: ff. 8, 9v, 12, 71, 73, 75, 134v, 136, 141, 142v, 144, 144v, 155, 164, 166, 191, 193, 196v, 197v, 198, 206, 217. Scenes of ff. 116v, 139, 143v, 145v, 145v, 162, 167-176v, 181v, 239, 267, 278v, 282r, 286.}} Four small miniatures have been attributed to the one whom Meiss designates as the \"Fifth Master\".{{efn|Folios 160, 161, 186v, 199v}} A single page by the [[Limbourg brothers]], the ''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'', was added to the manuscript around 1412.<ref>Husband, p. 43</ref>\n[[File:Jesus_betrayed_by_Judas,_Petites_Heures.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.85| ''Hours of the Passion''. Le Noir's miniature showing Jesus' arrest in the [[Gethsemane|garden at Gethsemane]] (fol. 76r)]]\nAmerican art historian [[Millard Meiss]] distinguishes five separate contributors to the work and identifies Le Noir with \"the Passion Master\", an anonymous illuminator so-called because he illustrated the [[Passion of Jesus|Passion]].<ref>Meiss, pp. 44, 160\u201369</ref> His characteristics have been described as \"rather cool, dusty colours\" and a \"delightful, often humorous depiction of animals\", also rocky scenery and agitated figures with expression.<ref>Hourihane, p. 472</ref> Jacquemart de Hesdin worked on the Hours of the Virgin. Characteristics are a representation of space influenced by Italian painting and a \"more realistic rendering of reality\" based on collaboration with [[Jean Bondol|Jan Boudolf]] of Bruges.<ref>Hourihane, pp. 453\u201354</ref> The styles of Jacquemart de Hesdin and Pseudo-Jacquemart are very similar because they worked together for more than 20 years. The latter has been described as copying the style of others rather than being creative.<ref>Hourihane, p. 133</ref>\n\nThe duke commissioned the ''Petites Heures'' around the same time as his older brother [[Charles V of France|Charles V]] acquired the ''[[Savoy Hours]]'', \"one of the grandest books of the period\" executed in about 1335\u201340.  To the ''Savoy Hours'', Charles added a new cover with jeweled clasps, further texts, and copious miniatures by the [[Master of the Bible of Jean de Sy]].  Comparison of the two books reveals that Jean de France modeled the content and structure of the ''Petites Heures'' on his brother's manuscript, which had \"clearly aroused his competitive spririt, and no doubt, envy.\"<ref>Husband, p. 27</ref>{{efn|For further analysis of the two books, see: Roger S. Wieck's 2005 essay \"Bibliophilic Jealousy and the Manuscript Patronage of Jean, Duc de Berry\".}}\n\nIn the ''Petites Heures'' Berry pays homage to his parents, [[Jean the Good]] and [[Bonne of Luxembourg]], through instructive prayers and texts copied from their respective books.<ref>Kinch, p. 134</ref>\n\n==Selected miniatures==\n[[File:D\u00e9part pour un p\u00e8lerinage - Petites Heures du duc de Berry - BNF Lat18014 f288v.jpg|thumb|upright|''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'']]\n''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'' (fol. 288v) is established as by the [[Limbourg brothers]], the third such image commissioned by the duke of a personal itinerary with an angel pointing the way. I was perhaps intended as a talisman; Husband notes that the duke \"is clearly an older man, the angel's guidance may not be entirely bound to the earthly realm.\"<ref>Husband, p. 43</ref>\n\n[[File:Petites heures du duc Jean de Berry fol 282r (d\u00e9tail).jpg|left|thumb |upright|''Tale of the Three Dead and the Three Living'']]\nThe ''Tale of the Three Dead and the Three Living'' (fol. 282r) is a relatively common form of [[memento mori]], found in both medieval art and poetry (cf. ''[[The Three Dead Kings]]''). Berry, \"veritably obsessed with self-display\", associates himself with the tale in several of his commissions, the images providing an opportunity to display \"ostentatious humility\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eSYzAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA134 Kinch, p.134]</ref> The text is copied from his [[Psalter of Bonne de Luxembourg|mother's psalter]].<ref name=k135>Kinch, p. 135</ref> Prefaced as a \"moult merueilleuse et horrible histoire\" (\"mournful and horrible history\")<ref name=k135/> it describes an encounter between three young men and three dead men in different stages of decomposition. The first apparition says \"What you are, we were, what we are, you will be\", the second reminds them that death treats rich and poor equally, the third adds that there is no escape from their fate.<ref>Deuchler, Florens. [https://www.metmuseum.org/pubs/bulletins/1/pdf/3258542.pdf.bannered.pdf \"Looking at Bonne of Luxembourg's Prayer Book\"] Metropolitan Museum of Art</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n[[File:Petites Heures de Jean de Berry john baptist.jpg| thumb |upright|''John the Baptist in the Wilderness'']]\n''John the Baptist in the Wilderness'' (fol.&nbsp;208r) is identified by [[Millard Meiss|Meiss]] as an example of the Passion Master's later style, \"which displays a new interest in the problems of relating depth\"<ref>Hourihane, p. 133</ref> It is an early example of a new trend in depictions of John, where the harsh desert setting was replaced with a fertile landscape, most probably inspired by Fra [[Domenico Cavalca]]'s ''Life of St. John the Baptist'' (1320\u201342), in which \"the desert was described as a place of great natural beauty, full of flowers, trees, and animals.\"<ref>Tzeutschler Lurie, p. 93</ref>\n\n[[File:7 Jean Le Noir. Miniature from Petites Heurs du Duc Jean de Berry 1372-75 Paris, Bibliotheque nationale de France..jpg|left| thumb |upright | ''Calendar for May'']]\nThe ''Calendar for May'' by Pseudo-Jacquemart. (fol.&nbsp;3r) is an example of iconography first used by [[Jean Pucelle]] in the ''[[Belleville Breviary]]''. Each month of the year shows an apostle, representative of the [[New Testament]], and a prophet of the [[Old Testament]]. The prophet submits a veiled prophecy which is explained by the apostle as an article of faith, while simultaneously, the prophet gives the apostle a stone from the synagogue, which as the months progress is reduced to a ruin.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33 Hulse, p. 33]</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n[[File:Harrowhell.jpg| thumb |upright|''The Harrowing of Hell'']]\n''The Harrowing of Hell'' is thought to have been started by Le Noir and completed by Pseudo-Jacquemart (fol.&nbsp;166). The [[Harrowing of Hell]] is derived from the [[Apostles' Creed]] and the [[Athanasian Creed]], which state that Jesus descended into Hell before his resurrection in order to save the righteous who had come before his earthly ministry.{{cn|date=December 2016}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Belles Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry|Belles Heures]]'' of Jean, Duc de Berry\n* ''[[Tr\u00e8s Riches Heures du Duc de Berry|Tr\u00e8s Riches Heures]]'' of Jean, Duc de Berry\n* ''[[Turin-Milan Hours]]'', owned and perhaps commissioned by Berry\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|title=The Art of Illumination: The Limbourg Brothers and the Belle Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry|first=Timothy B. |last=Husband |year=2008| publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York | url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/metpublications/The_Art_of_Illumination_The_Limbourg_Brothers_and_the_Belles_Heures_of_Jean_de_France_Duc_de_Berr| isbn=978-1-58839-294-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meiss |first=Millard |authorlink=Millard Meiss |title=French Painting in the Time of Jean De Berry: The Late Fourteenth Century and the Patronage of the Duke (2 Vols) |location=London |publisher=[[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]] |isbn=978-0714813097 |pages=44, 160\u201369}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Medieval Art and Architecture |first= Colum |last=Hourihane |year=2002 |publisher=OUP |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=FtlMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA472 |isbn=978-0-19539-536-5 |volume=2}}\n* [http://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc784809 Latin 18014] archivesetmanuscrits.bnf\n* {{cite journal|title=A Newly Discovered Eyckian St. John the Baptist in a Landscape|first=Ann|last=Tzeutschler Lurie|date=April 1981|volume=68|issue=4|pages=87\u2013109|journal=The Bulletin of the Cleveland Museum of Art|jstor=25159721}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hulse|first=Clark|title=The Rule of Art: Literature and Painting in the Renaissance|year=1990|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-36052-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33 33]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kinch|first=Ashby|title=Imago Mortis: Mediating Images of Death in Late Medieval Culture|year=2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-24581-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b8449684q.r=Horae+ad+usum+Parisiensem+ou+Petites+heures+de+Jean+de+Berry.langEN Digitised copy of the Petites Heures] at the BNF\n* [http://www.facsimilefinder.com/facsimiles/petites-heures-of-the-duke-of-berry-facsimile Paris, Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France, Ms. lat. 18014 / Petites Heures of the Duke of Berry] facsimilefinder.com\n\n[[Category:Illuminated books of hours]]\n[[Category:Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France collections]]\n[[Category:14th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:15th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artwork\n | title             = Les Petites Heures de Jean de Berry\n | italic title      = no\n | image             = Jacquemart de Hesdin 002.jpg\n | image_size        = 250px\n | caption           = ''The Annunciation'',<br> miniature by [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]]<br>and [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]]\n | alt               =\n | artist            = {{plainlist|\n* [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]]\n* [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]]\n* [[Pseudo-Jacquemart]]\n* [[Master of the Trinity]]\n* [[Limbourg brothers]]\n}}\n | year              = 1375\u20131390\n | medium            = Illuminated [[book of hours]]\n | height_metric     = 21.5\n | width_metric      = 14.5\n | museum            = [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]\n | city              = Paris, France\n | catalogue         = Ms. Lat.18014\n}}\nThe '''Petites Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry''' is an illuminated [[book of hours]] commissioned by [[John, Duke of Berry]] between 1375 and 1385\u201390. It is known for its ornate [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature]] leaves and border decorations.\n\nSeveral artists were employed in the production. It was completed in two separate stages, each with a distinctive style. The earlier leaves were painted by artists influenced by [[Jean Pucelle]], the later by artists working in the vanguard of the [[International Gothic]] period of Gothic art. Because of this, the ''Petites Heures'' exemplifies the \"rupture in style\" that occurred in French illumination in the final two decades of the fourteenth century.<ref>[http://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc784809 Latin 18014] archivesetmanuscrits.bnf</ref>\n\nA high-resolution facsimile was published in 1988, with monographs by Avril, Dunlop and [[William Brunsdon Yapp|Yapp]].<ref>Husband, p. 45</ref>\n\n== History ==\nJean de Berry commissioned six books of hours between 1375 and 1416. The first, the ''Petites Heures'',<ref>Husband, pp. 24\u201325</ref> contains 182 miniatures. Work started c. 1375 but was interrupted in 1380 and the book was not completed until 1385\u201390.<ref>Husband, p.43</ref> It is now housed at the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] under the reference ms. lat. 18014.<ref>Husband, p. 25</ref>\n\nThe [[limner]] [[Jean Le Noir (illuminator)|Jean Le Noir]], a pupil of Jean Pucelle, started work on the illuminations.<ref>Hourihane, p. 472</ref> By the time of his death in 1380, only nine miniatures had been completed.{{efn|Meiss and Avril attribute to Jean Le Noir the miniatures of folios 53, 76r, 79v, 82, 83v, 86v, 89v, 92v and 94v, as well as the figures of the angel Gabriel and the Virgin of the Annunciation (f.22) and those of the beggar and his children in the left margin of the 97v. Le Noir's hand can also be seen in the decorative plantlife and the delicate design of the filigree initials. He probably worked on 40v (Announcement to the Shepherds), 207 (Birth of John the Baptist), 208 (John the Baptist in the Wilderness), 212v (Dance of Salome)}} In 1384 the duke engaged [[Jacquemart de Hesdin]];<ref>Hourihane, p. 453</ref> completion of the book was left to him{{efn|Jacquemart de Hesdin's hand is seen in folios 8, 38, 40v, 42v, 45v, 203, 212, 214}} and an assistant known as the Master of the Trinity,{{efn|Named for his contributions to Hours of the Trinity, he executed five of that offices' eight miniatures: ff. 183, 188, 189, 192, 194v. His hand is recognized in the painting of the Coronation of the Virgin, in four paintings of the office of the Holy Ghost, and Lamentations (158, 163). Also in the series of offices of the week (137v, 140v, 141v) and in some paintings depicting prayers (100v, 103v, 196, 198v). Meiss also sees his hand in the great paintings of the office of John the Baptist: f. 203, 209v, 211, 214.}} and to another artist known as [[Pseudo-Jacquemart]], who painted in some of the underdrawings left by Jean le Noir, as well as contributing his own compositions.{{efn|In addition to the calendar, Pseudo-Jacquemart completed the scenes begun by Jean Le Noir: ff. 8, 9v, 12, 71, 73, 75, 134v, 136, 141, 142v, 144, 144v, 155, 164, 166, 191, 193, 196v, 197v, 198, 206, 217. Scenes of ff. 116v, 139, 143v, 145v, 145v, 162, 167-176v, 181v, 239, 267, 278v, 282r, 286.}} Four small miniatures have been attributed to the one whom Meiss designates as the \"Fifth Master\".{{efn|Folios 160, 161, 186v, 199v}} A single page by the [[Limbourg brothers]], the ''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'', was added to the manuscript around 1412.<ref>Husband, p. 43</ref>\n[[File:Jesus_betrayed_by_Judas,_Petites_Heures.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.85| ''Hours of the Passion''. Le Noir's miniature showing Jesus' arrest in the [[Gethsemane|garden at Gethsemane]] (fol. 76r)]]\nAmerican art historian [[Millard Meiss]] distinguishes five separate contributors to the work and identifies Le Noir with \"the Passion Master\", an anonymous illuminator so-called because he illustrated the [[Passion of Jesus|Passion]].<ref>Meiss, pp. 44, 160\u201369</ref> His characteristics have been described as \"rather cool, dusty colours\" and a \"delightful, often humorous depiction of animals\", also rocky scenery and agitated figures with expression.<ref>Hourihane, p. 472</ref> Jacquemart de Hesdin worked on the Hours of the Virgin. Characteristics are a representation of space influenced by Italian painting and a \"more realistic rendering of reality\" based on collaboration with [[Jean Bondol|Jan Boudolf]] of Bruges.<ref>Hourihane, pp. 453\u201354</ref> The styles of Jacquemart de Hesdin and Pseudo-Jacquemart are very similar because they worked together for more than 20 years. The latter has been described as copying the style of others rather than being creative.<ref>Hourihane, p. 133</ref>\n\nThe duke commissioned the ''Petites Heures'' around the same time as his older brother [[Charles V of France|Charles V]] acquired the ''[[Savoy Hours]]'', \"one of the grandest books of the period\" executed in about 1335\u201340.  To the ''Savoy Hours'', Charles added a new cover with jeweled clasps, further texts, and copious miniatures by the [[Master of the Bible of Jean de Sy]].  Comparison of the two books reveals that Jean de France modeled the content and structure of the ''Petites Heures'' on his brother's manuscript, which had \"clearly aroused his competitive spririt, and no doubt, envy.\"<ref>Husband, p. 27</ref>{{efn|For further analysis of the two books, see: Roger S. Wieck's 2005 essay \"Bibliophilic Jealousy and the Manuscript Patronage of Jean, Duc de Berry\".}}\n\nIn the ''Petites Heures'' Berry pays homage to his parents, [[Jean the Good]] and [[Bonne of Luxembourg]], through instructive prayers and texts copied from their respective books.<ref>Kinch, p. 134</ref>\n\n==Selected miniatures==\n[[File:\"Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip\" Limbourg brothers.jpeg|thumb|upright|''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'']]\n''Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip'' (fol. 288v) is established as by the [[Limbourg brothers]], the third such image commissioned by the duke of a personal itinerary with an angel pointing the way. I was perhaps intended as a talisman; Husband notes that the duke \"is clearly an older man, the angel's guidance may not be entirely bound to the earthly realm.\"<ref>Husband, p. 43</ref>\n\n[[File:Petites heures du duc Jean de Berry fol 282r (d\u00e9tail).jpg|left|thumb |upright|''Tale of the Three Dead and the Three Living'']]\nThe ''Tale of the Three Dead and the Three Living'' (fol. 282r) is a relatively common form of [[memento mori]], found in both medieval art and poetry (cf. ''[[The Three Dead Kings]]''). Berry, \"veritably obsessed with self-display\", associates himself with the tale in several of his commissions, the images providing an opportunity to display \"ostentatious humility\".<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=eSYzAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA134 Kinch, p.134]</ref> The text is copied from his [[Psalter of Bonne de Luxembourg|mother's psalter]].<ref name=k135>Kinch, p. 135</ref> Prefaced as a \"moult merueilleuse et horrible histoire\" (\"mournful and horrible history\")<ref name=k135/> it describes an encounter between three young men and three dead men in different stages of decomposition. The first apparition says \"What you are, we were, what we are, you will be\", the second reminds them that death treats rich and poor equally, the third adds that there is no escape from their fate.<ref>Deuchler, Florens. [https://www.metmuseum.org/pubs/bulletins/1/pdf/3258542.pdf.bannered.pdf \"Looking at Bonne of Luxembourg's Prayer Book\"] Metropolitan Museum of Art</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n[[File:Petites Heures de Jean de Berry john baptist.jpg| thumb |upright|''John the Baptist in the Wilderness'']]\n''John the Baptist in the Wilderness'' (fol.&nbsp;208r) is identified by [[Millard Meiss|Meiss]] as an example of the Passion Master's later style, \"which displays a new interest in the problems of relating depth\"<ref>Hourihane, p. 133</ref> It is an early example of a new trend in depictions of John, where the harsh desert setting was replaced with a fertile landscape, most probably inspired by Fra [[Domenico Cavalca]]'s ''Life of St. John the Baptist'' (1320\u201342), in which \"the desert was described as a place of great natural beauty, full of flowers, trees, and animals.\"<ref>Tzeutschler Lurie, p. 93</ref>\n\n[[File:7 Jean Le Noir. Miniature from Petites Heurs du Duc Jean de Berry 1372-75 Paris, Bibliotheque nationale de France..jpg|left| thumb |upright | ''Calendar for May'']]\nThe ''Calendar for May'' by Pseudo-Jacquemart. (fol.&nbsp;3r) is an example of iconography first used by [[Jean Pucelle]] in the ''[[Belleville Breviary]]''. Each month of the year shows an apostle, representative of the [[New Testament]], and a prophet of the [[Old Testament]]. The prophet submits a veiled prophecy which is explained by the apostle as an article of faith, while simultaneously, the prophet gives the apostle a stone from the synagogue, which as the months progress is reduced to a ruin.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33 Hulse, p. 33]</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n[[File:Harrowhell.jpg| thumb |upright|''The Harrowing of Hell'']]\n''The Harrowing of Hell'' is thought to have been started by Le Noir and completed by Pseudo-Jacquemart (fol.&nbsp;166). The [[Harrowing of Hell]] is derived from the [[Apostles' Creed]] and the [[Athanasian Creed]], which state that Jesus descended into Hell before his resurrection in order to save the righteous who had come before his earthly ministry.{{cn|date=December 2016}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Belles Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry|Belles Heures]]'' of Jean, Duc de Berry\n* ''[[Tr\u00e8s Riches Heures du Duc de Berry|Tr\u00e8s Riches Heures]]'' of Jean, Duc de Berry\n* ''[[Turin-Milan Hours]]'', owned and perhaps commissioned by Berry\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|title=The Art of Illumination: The Limbourg Brothers and the Belle Heures of Jean de France, Duc de Berry|first=Timothy B. |last=Husband |year=2008| publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York | url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/metpublications/The_Art_of_Illumination_The_Limbourg_Brothers_and_the_Belles_Heures_of_Jean_de_France_Duc_de_Berr| isbn=978-1-58839-294-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Meiss |first=Millard |authorlink=Millard Meiss |title=French Painting in the Time of Jean De Berry: The Late Fourteenth Century and the Patronage of the Duke (2 Vols) |location=London |publisher=[[Phaidon Press|Phaidon]] |isbn=978-0714813097 |pages=44, 160\u201369}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Medieval Art and Architecture |first= Colum |last=Hourihane |year=2002 |publisher=OUP |url=https://books.google.de/books?id=FtlMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA472 |isbn=978-0-19539-536-5 |volume=2}}\n* [http://archivesetmanuscrits.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cc784809 Latin 18014] archivesetmanuscrits.bnf\n* {{cite journal|title=A Newly Discovered Eyckian St. John the Baptist in a Landscape|first=Ann|last=Tzeutschler Lurie|date=April 1981|volume=68|issue=4|pages=87\u2013109|journal=The Bulletin of the Cleveland Museum of Art|jstor=25159721}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hulse|first=Clark|title=The Rule of Art: Literature and Painting in the Renaissance|year=1990|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-36052-2|page=[https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33 33]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/ruleofartliterat0000huls/page/33}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kinch|first=Ashby|title=Imago Mortis: Mediating Images of Death in Late Medieval Culture|year=2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-24581-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/btv1b8449684q.r=Horae+ad+usum+Parisiensem+ou+Petites+heures+de+Jean+de+Berry.langEN Digitised copy of the Petites Heures] at the BNF\n* [http://www.facsimilefinder.com/facsimiles/petites-heures-of-the-duke-of-berry-facsimile Paris, Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France, Ms. lat. 18014 / Petites Heures of the Duke of Berry] facsimilefinder.com\n\n[[Category:Illuminated books of hours]]\n[[Category:Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France collections]]\n[[Category:14th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:15th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n", "name_user": "Achim55", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:\"Duke of Berry Setting off on a Trip\" Limbourg brothers.jpeg\u2192File:D\u00e9part pour un p\u00e8lerinage - Petites Heures du duc de Berry - BNF Lat18014 f288v.jpglinkfix: file renamed on Commons", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petites_Heures_of_Jean_de_France,_Duc_de_Berry"}
{"title_page": "Mateusz Mol\u0119da", "text_new": "[[File:Moleda-2019.jpg|thumb|upright|Mateusz Mol\u0119da, 2019]]\n'''Mateusz Krzysztof Maksymilian Mol\u0119da''' (born December 4, 1986) is a German-Polish conductor.\n\n== Life ==\n\nMateusz Mol\u0119da was born in [[Dresden]], Germany, into a family of musicians. His parents Alicja Borkowska-Mol\u0119da (born 1952) and Krzysztof Mol\u0119da (born 1953) are both [[opera]] singers and sang for more than two decades title and major roles at European opera houses like the [[Semper Opera House]], the [[Komische Oper Berlin]], the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], the [[Leipzig Opera]] and the [[Prague State Opera]]. Mol\u0119da holds the German and Polish citizenship and lives in [[Hanover]], Germany. He is fluent in [[German language|German]], [[Polish]], [[English]], [[French]] and [[Russian]].\n\n== Education ==\n\nMol\u0119da started to play the piano at the age of six and studied later at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik, Theater und Medien Hannover]] in the class of [[Arie Vardi]], considered one of the most distinguished piano teachers of the world, who also serves as conductor of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] for more than twenty years. He continued his studies in the area of historical keyboard instruments and [[historical performance practice]] in cooperation with Zvi Meniker.\n\nMol\u0119da has received important musical impulses from his mentor [[Marek Janowski]], for whom he worked by personal request also as assistant with the [[Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Dresden Philharmonic]] and the [[Frankfurt Radio Symphony Orchestra]]. By sharing his varied experiences, Janowski has profoundly influenced Mol\u0119da's artistic development in the spirit of the traditional German conducting school.\n\n== Collaboration with orchestras ==\n\nMol\u0119da conducted for the first time an orchestra at the age of nineteen. He guest-conducted renowned orchestras in more than 10 countries of the world, among others in Germany, Poland, Spain, Denmark, Albania, South Korea, Japan as well as in South Africa. He has worked among others with the Deutsches Kammerorchester Berlin, the [[Nuremberg Symphony]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.br-klassik.de/aktuell/news-kritik/freundschaftskonzert-koszalin-polen-nuernberg-symphoniker100.html | title=N\u00fcrnberger Symphoniker in Koszalin: Freundschaftskonzert zum Stadtjubil\u00e4um &#124; BR-Klassik| date=13 June 2016}}</ref>, the [[Jena Philharmonic]], the Heidelberg Philharmonic, the Folkwang Kammerorchester Essen, the Staatskapelle Schwerin, the Carl Nielsen Academy Orchestra, the [[Aalborg Symfoniorkester]], the [[Aarhus Symfoniorkester]], the [[Odense Symfoniorkester]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://odensesymfoni.dk/koncerter/romantic-overload/ |title = Romantic Overload}}</ref> and the NFM Wroclaw Philharmonic<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nfm.wroclaw.pl/en/component/nfmcalendar/event/5608 |title = NFM Wroc\u0142aw Philharmonic in Legnica}}</ref>.\n\n== Notable concerts ==\n\nWith his performance of Beethoven's [[Choral Fantasy (Beethoven)|Choral Fantasy]] at the formal function of the Federal Government on the [[Day of German Unity]] on 3 October 2007, Mol\u0119da commanded attention throughout Germany. The concert was broadcast live by the German TV channel [[ZDF]] with over eight million viewers.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UKxy5ijCM0Q</ref>\n\nOn November 8, 2018, Mol\u0119da conducted the world premiere of the Concerto for [[Hammond organ]] by Danish composer [[Anders Koppel]], the first composition of this genre ever.<ref>https://www.aarhussymfoni.dk/koncert/kaerlighed-doed-og-forvandling/</ref> <ref>https://slippedisc.com/2019/01/the-first-concerto-for-hammond-organ-and-orchestra/</ref> <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bEjFa62zuUw</ref>\n\n== TV and radio recordings ==\n\nNumerous radio and television recordings are available, including for [[BR Klassik]], [[MDR Kultur]], [[Danmarks Radio|DR 2]] and [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Official|http://www.mateuszmoleda.de|Website (German/Polish/English)}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moleda, Mateusz}}\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Moleda-2019.jpg|thumb|upright|Mateusz Mol\u0119da, 2019]]\n'''Mateusz Krzysztof Maksymilian Mol\u0119da''' (born December 4, 1986) is a German-Polish conductor.\n\n== Life ==\n\nMateusz Mol\u0119da was born in [[Dresden]], Germany, into a family of musicians. His parents Alicja Borkowska-Mol\u0119da (born 1952) and Krzysztof Mol\u0119da (born 1953) are both [[opera]] singers and sang for more than two decades title and major roles at European opera houses like the [[Semper Opera House]], the [[Komische Oper Berlin]], the [[Deutsche Oper Berlin]], the [[Leipzig Opera]] and the [[Prague State Opera]]. Mol\u0119da holds the German and Polish citizenship and lives in [[Hanover]], Germany. He is fluent in [[German]], [[Polish]], [[English]], [[French]] and [[Russian]].\n\n== Education ==\n\nMol\u0119da started to play the piano at the age of six and studied later at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik, Theater und Medien Hannover]] in the class of [[Arie Vardi]], considered one of the most distinguished piano teachers of the world, who also serves as conductor of the [[Israel Philharmonic Orchestra]] for more than twenty years. He continued his studies in the area of historical keyboard instruments and [[historical performance practice]] in cooperation with Zvi Meniker.\n\nMol\u0119da has received important musical impulses from his mentor [[Marek Janowski]], for whom he worked by personal request also as assistant with the [[Berlin Radio Symphony Orchestra]], the [[Dresden Philharmonic]] and the [[Frankfurt Radio Symphony Orchestra]]. By sharing his varied experiences, Janowski has profoundly influenced Mol\u0119da's artistic development in the spirit of the traditional German conducting school.\n\n== Collaboration with orchestras ==\n\nMol\u0119da conducted for the first time an orchestra at the age of nineteen. He guest-conducted renowned orchestras in more than 10 countries of the world, among others in Germany, Poland, Spain, Denmark, Albania, South Korea, Japan as well as in South Africa. He has worked among others with the Deutsches Kammerorchester Berlin, the [[Nuremberg Symphony]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.br-klassik.de/aktuell/news-kritik/freundschaftskonzert-koszalin-polen-nuernberg-symphoniker100.html | title=N\u00fcrnberger Symphoniker in Koszalin: Freundschaftskonzert zum Stadtjubil\u00e4um &#124; BR-Klassik| date=13 June 2016}}</ref>, the [[Jena Philharmonic]], the Heidelberg Philharmonic, the Folkwang Kammerorchester Essen, the Staatskapelle Schwerin, the Carl Nielsen Academy Orchestra, the [[Aalborg Symfoniorkester]], the [[Aarhus Symfoniorkester]], the [[Odense Symfoniorkester]]<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://odensesymfoni.dk/koncerter/romantic-overload/ |title = Romantic Overload}}</ref> and the NFM Wroclaw Philharmonic<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nfm.wroclaw.pl/en/component/nfmcalendar/event/5608 |title = NFM Wroc\u0142aw Philharmonic in Legnica}}</ref>.\n\n== Notable concerts ==\n\nWith his performance of Beethoven's [[Choral Fantasy (Beethoven)|Choral Fantasy]] at the formal function of the Federal Government on the [[Day of German Unity]] on 3 October 2007, Mol\u0119da commanded attention throughout Germany. The concert was broadcast live by the German TV channel [[ZDF]] with over eight million viewers.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UKxy5ijCM0Q</ref>\n\nOn November 8, 2018, Mol\u0119da conducted the world premiere of the Concerto for [[Hammond organ]] by Danish composer [[Anders Koppel]], the first composition of this genre ever.<ref>https://www.aarhussymfoni.dk/koncert/kaerlighed-doed-og-forvandling/</ref> <ref>https://slippedisc.com/2019/01/the-first-concerto-for-hammond-organ-and-orchestra/</ref> <ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bEjFa62zuUw</ref>\n\n== TV and radio recordings ==\n\nNumerous radio and television recordings are available, including for [[BR Klassik]], [[MDR Kultur]], [[Danmarks Radio|DR 2]] and [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*{{Official|http://www.mateuszmoleda.de|Website (German/Polish/English)}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moleda, Mateusz}}\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dresden]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGerman(link changed toGerman language) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mateusz_Mol%C4%99da"}
{"title_page": "Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103\n| image = Tudor Baluta (cropped) - Sweden vs Romania 23 March 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption = B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 with [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in 2019\n| fullname = Tudor Cristian B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1999|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Craiova]], Romania\n| height = 1.91m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]], [[Defender (association football)|defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 2007\u20132013\n| youthclubs1 = [[Gheorghe Popescu]] Football School\n| youthyears2 = 2013\u20132015\n| youthclubs2 = [[Gheorghe Hagi Football Academy|Gheorghe Hagi Academy]]\n| currentclub = [[ADO Den Haag]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| years1 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs1 = [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]\n| caps1 = 53\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[ADO Den Haag|ADO Den Haag]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 3\n| goals3 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam1 = [[Romania national under-19 football team|Romania U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Romania national football team|Romania]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 7\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| pcupdate = {{date|2019-05-20}}\n| ntupdate = {{date|2019-11-18}}\n}}\n'''Tudor Cristian B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8tudor kristi\u02c8an b\u0259\u02c8lut\u0361s\u0259}}; born 27 March 1999) is a Romanian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Eredivisie]] side [[ADO Den Haag]], on loan from [[Premier League]] side [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], and the [[Romania national football team|Romanian national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Viitorul Constan\u021ba===\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 began his career in native [[Craiova]], joining the [[Gheorghe Popescu]] Football School at age 8. Six years later, he moved to [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]'s [[Gheorghe Hagi Football Academy|academy]].<ref name=\"gica_popescu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sport.ro/nationala/determinare-incredibila-baiat-destept-fotbalist-complet-gica-popescu-cuvinte-uriase-pentru-tudor-baluta.html|title=\"Determinare incredibila, baiat destept, fotbalist complet!\" Gica Popescu, cuvinte uriase pentru Tudor Baluta|trans-title=\"Incredible determination, a smart boy, complete footballer!\" Gic\u0103 Popescu, giant words for Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103|publisher=[[Sport.ro]]|language=Romanian|date=19 June 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made his professional debut in the [[Liga I]] on 2 May 2016, aged 17, replacing [[Ianis Hagi]] in the 54th minute of a 6\u20131 thrashing of [[ASA 2013 T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219|ASA T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digisport.ro/live-text/viitorul-targu-mures-6-1-echipa-lui-gica-hagi-a-obtinut-prima-victorie-in-play-off-301140|title=Viitorul - T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219 6-1. Echipa lui Gic\u0103 Hagi a ob\u021binut prima victorie in play-off|trans-title=Viitorul - T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219 6\u20131. Gic\u0103 Hagi's team obtained its first victory in the championship play-offs|publisher=[[Digi Sport (Romania)|Digi Sport]]|language=Romanian|date=2 May 2016|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"debut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reporterntv.ro/stire/hagi-anunta-un-nume-de-viitor-tudor-baluta|title=Hagi anun\u021b\u0103 un nume de Viitor: Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103!|trans-title=Hagi announces a name for the future: Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103!|publisher=Reporter NTV|language=Romanian|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tudor Baluta - 24. August 2017.jpg|thumb|left|160px|B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 playing against [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]], 24 August 2017.]]\nHe did not feature in any senior games in the [[2016\u201317 Liga I|next season]] as Viitorul won the first league title in its history, but started appearing frequently for the side since the summer of 2017. On 24 August that year, B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 recorded his [[UEFA|European]] debut in a [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|UEFA Europa League play-off round]] 0\u20134 loss to [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2018/matches/round=2000889/match=2021992/index.html|title=Salzburg 4\u20130 Viitorul|publisher=UEFA|date=24 August 2017|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> On 30 August 2018, he scored his first goal\u2014and the only of the match\u2014in a league win over [[FC Astra Giurgiu|Astra Giurgiu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prosport.ro/fotbal-intern/liga-1/viitorul-astra-1-0-baluta-a-marcat-golul-victoriei-in-prelungiri-hagi-a-fost-trimis-in-tribune-dupa-ce-s-a-contrat-cu-staff-ul-advers-giurgiuvenii-au-evoluat-mai-bine-de-o-repriza-in-10-oameni-17537276|title=Viitorul - Astra 1-0. B\u0103lu\u0163\u0103 a marcat golul victoriei \u00een prelungiri! Hagi a fost trimis \u00een tribune dup\u0103 ce s-a contrat cu staff-ul advers, giurgiuvenii au evoluat mai bine de o repriz\u0103 \u00een 10 oameni|trans-title=Viitorul - Astra 1\u20130. B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 scored the winner in the injury-time! Hagi was sent out after a conflict with the opposing staff, the Giurgiu men played more than half of the game with 10 footballers|publisher=[[ProSport]]|language=Romanian|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 agreed to a three-and-a-half-year contract with English club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 31 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-romania-international/|title=ALBION SIGN ROMANIA INTERNATIONAL|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made the bench for the first time for the ''Seagulls'' in a 2\u20131 away win over [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] in the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] on 27 August 2019 and was named on the bench in a [[Premier League]] fixture for the first time in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 14 September. He remained an unused substitute in both fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49402996 |title=Bristol Rovers v Brighton & Hove Albion - BBC Sport |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 August 2019 |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617984|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-1 Burnley: Jeff Hendrick scores in stoppage time to earn visitors a point - BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made his debut for the Sussex club in the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] playing the whole match in the 3\u20131 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 25 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49736853|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-3 Aston Villa: Conor Hourihane scores win - BBC Sport |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2019|accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> \n\n====Viitorul Constan\u021ba (loan)====\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 was immediately loaned back to Viitorul Constan\u021ba for the remainder of the [[2018\u201319 Liga I|campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-romania-international/|title=ALBION SIGN ROMANIA INTERNATIONAL|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> Press reported the transfer fee at [[Euro|\u20ac]]3 million, which made him the club's most expensive sale at the time, tied with [[Florinel Coman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bzi.ro/tudor-baluta-a-semnat-gica-hagi-si-a-egalat-recordul-ce-salariu-va-avea-mijlocasul-in-premier-league-681705|title=Tudor Baluta a semnat! Gica Hagi si-a egalat recordul! Ce salariu va avea mijlocasul, \u00een Premier League|trans-title=Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 has signed! Gic\u0103 Hagi equaled his record! What salary the midfielder will have in the Premier League|publisher=BZI|language=Romanian|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019|quote=Thus, Hagi equaled his record for the most expensive transfer in the history of the club. For Florinel Coman, Gigi Becali had also paid a total of 3 million euros.}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May, he was a starter and played the full match in the [[Cupa Rom\u00e2niei]] final 2\u20131 success against Astra Giurgiu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziare.com/viitorul/stiri-viitorul/viitorul-lui-hagi-castiga-cupa-romaniei-dupa-o-finala-complicata-cu-astra-1562953|title=Viitorul lui Hagi castiga Cupa Romaniei dupa o finala complicata cu Astra|trans-title=Hagi's Viitorul wins the Romanian Cup after a difficult final with Astra|publisher=Ziare|language=Romanian|date=25 May 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 earned his first senior [[Cap (sports)|cap]] for [[Romania national football team|Romania]] on 31 May 2018, entering as a 71st-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for former Viitorul Constan\u021ba teammate [[Drago\u0219 Nedelcu]] in a 3\u20132 [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] victory against [[Chile national football team|Chile]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digisport.ro/fotbal/echipa-nationala/romania-chile-1700-tricolorii-in-linie-dreapta-inainte-de-liga-natiunilor-456136|title=Rom\u00e2nia - Chile 3-2. Rezerva Budescu a adus victoria tricolorilor. Sud-americanii au jucat o or\u0103 \u00een 10|trans-title=Romania - Chile 3\u20132. Substitute Budescu brought victory for \"the Tricolours\". The South Americans played for an hour in ten men|publisher=Digi Sport|language=Romanian|date=31 May 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite not playing in the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualification phase]], he was selected in [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]]'s squad for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] in [[Italy]]. B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 scored on his debut against [[Croatia national under-21 football team|Croatia]] on 19 June that year, which ended in a 4\u20131 win for his side.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2019/matches/round=2000799/match=2025986/|title=Romania 4\u20131 Croatia|publisher=UEFA.com|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> He recorded three more games as ''Tricolorii mici'' were eliminated by [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification#Semi-finals|semi-finals]], following a 2\u20134 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2019/matches/round=2000800/match=2027440/index.html|title=Germany 4\u20132 Romania|publisher=UEFA.com|date=27 June 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 is deployed primarily as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], but started out as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].<ref name=\"debut\"/> He has been likened to former Romanian international and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] captain [[Gheorghe Popescu]], also a native of [[Dolj County]], who in his turn described B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 as an \"intelligent player\" with \"exceptional qualities\".<ref name=\"gica_popescu\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|1 October 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway|tudor-cristian-blu/408625}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Domestic Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Liga I|2015\u201316]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Liga I]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Liga I|2016\u201317]]\n|0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Liga I|2017\u201318]]\n|24||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||26||0\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Liga I|2018\u201319]]\n|27||2||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0||30||3\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!53!!2!!4!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5!!0!!62!!2\n|-\n|[[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. season|2019\u201320]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|[[ADO Den Haag|ADO den Haag]]\n|[[2019\u201320 Eredivisie|2019\u201320]]\n|[[Eredivisie]]\n|3||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|[[2018\u201319 Serie B|\u2013]]||colspan=\"2\"|[[2018\u201319 Serie B|\u2013]]||3||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Total\n!56!!2!!4!!0!!1!!0!!5!!0!!66!!2\n|}\n\n{{notelist}} \n\n[[File:UEFA EURO qualifiers Sweden vs Romaina 20190323 Emil Forsberg and Tudor Baluta 20 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|250px|B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 (left) in a match with [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in March 2019.]]\n===International===\n{{updated|18 November 2019}}<ref name=EU>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=30314|title=Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103|publisher=European Football|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!National team!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Romania national football team|Romania]]\n|2018||3||0\n|-\n|2019||4||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total||7||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Viitorul Constan\u021ba'''\n*[[Liga I]]: [[2016\u201317 Liga I|2016\u201317]]\n*[[Cupa Rom\u00e2niei]]: [[2018\u201319 Cupa Rom\u00e2niei|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Supercupa Rom\u00e2niei]]: Runner-up [[2017 Supercupa Rom\u00e2niei|2017]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{RomanianSoccer|4394/tudor-baluta}}\n*{{Soccerway|tudor-cristian-blu/408625}}\n*{{UEFA player|250088881}}\n\n<!--{{Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. squad}}-->\n{{ADO Den Haag squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baluta, Tudor}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Craiova]]\n[[Category:Romanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Brighton & Hove Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:ADO Den Haag players]]\n[[Category:Romania youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania international footballers]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103\n| image = Tudor Baluta (cropped) - Sweden vs Romania 23 March 2019.jpg\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption = B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 with [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in 2019\n| fullname = Tudor Cristian B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1999|03|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Craiova]], Romania\n| height = 1.91m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]] / [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1 = 2007\u20132013\n| youthclubs1 = [[Gheorghe Popescu]] Football School\n| youthyears2 = 2013\u20132015\n| youthclubs2 = [[Gheorghe Hagi Football Academy|Gheorghe Hagi Academy]]\n| currentclub = [[ADO Den Haag]]\n| clubnumber = 5\n| years1 = 2015\u20132019\n| clubs1 = [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]\n| caps1 = 53\n| goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n| caps2 = 0\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[ADO Den Haag|ADO Den Haag]] (loan)\n| caps3 = 3\n| goals3 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| nationalteam1 = [[Romania national under-19 football team|Romania U19]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 6\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 7\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n| nationalyears3 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam3 = [[Romania national football team|Romania]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 7\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| pcupdate = {{date|2019-05-20}}\n| ntupdate = {{date|2019-11-18}}\n}}\n'''Tudor Cristian B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8tudor kristi\u02c8an b\u0259\u02c8lut\u0361s\u0259}}; born 27 March 1999) is a Romanian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Eredivisie]] side [[ADO Den Haag]], on loan from [[Premier League]] side [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], and the [[Romania national football team|Romanian national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Viitorul Constan\u021ba===\n\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 began his career in native [[Craiova]], joining the [[Gheorghe Popescu]] Football School at age 8. Six years later, he moved to [[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]'s [[Gheorghe Hagi Football Academy|academy]].<ref name=\"gica_popescu\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sport.ro/nationala/determinare-incredibila-baiat-destept-fotbalist-complet-gica-popescu-cuvinte-uriase-pentru-tudor-baluta.html|title=\"Determinare incredibila, baiat destept, fotbalist complet!\" Gica Popescu, cuvinte uriase pentru Tudor Baluta|trans-title=\"Incredible determination, a smart boy, complete footballer!\" Gic\u0103 Popescu, giant words for Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103|publisher=[[Sport.ro]]|language=Romanian|date=19 June 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made his professional debut in the [[Liga I]] on 2 May 2016, aged 17, replacing [[Ianis Hagi]] in the 54th minute of a 6\u20131 thrashing of [[ASA 2013 T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219|ASA T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digisport.ro/live-text/viitorul-targu-mures-6-1-echipa-lui-gica-hagi-a-obtinut-prima-victorie-in-play-off-301140|title=Viitorul - T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219 6-1. Echipa lui Gic\u0103 Hagi a ob\u021binut prima victorie in play-off|trans-title=Viitorul - T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219 6\u20131. Gic\u0103 Hagi's team obtained its first victory in the championship play-offs|publisher=[[Digi Sport (Romania)|Digi Sport]]|language=Romanian|date=2 May 2016|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"debut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reporterntv.ro/stire/hagi-anunta-un-nume-de-viitor-tudor-baluta|title=Hagi anun\u021b\u0103 un nume de Viitor: Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103!|trans-title=Hagi announces a name for the future: Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103!|publisher=Reporter NTV|language=Romanian|date=3 May 2016|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tudor Baluta - 24. August 2017.jpg|thumb|left|160px|B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 playing against [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in the [[UEFA Europa League]], 24 August 2017.]]\nHe did not feature in any senior games in the [[2016\u201317 Liga I|next season]] as Viitorul won the first league title in its history, but started appearing frequently for the side since the summer of 2017. On 24 August that year, B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 recorded his [[UEFA|European]] debut in a [[2017\u201318 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|UEFA Europa League play-off round]] 0\u20134 loss to [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2018/matches/round=2000889/match=2021992/index.html|title=Salzburg 4\u20130 Viitorul|publisher=UEFA|date=24 August 2017|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref> On 30 August 2018, he scored his first goal\u2014and the only of the match\u2014in a league win over [[FC Astra Giurgiu|Astra Giurgiu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prosport.ro/fotbal-intern/liga-1/viitorul-astra-1-0-baluta-a-marcat-golul-victoriei-in-prelungiri-hagi-a-fost-trimis-in-tribune-dupa-ce-s-a-contrat-cu-staff-ul-advers-giurgiuvenii-au-evoluat-mai-bine-de-o-repriza-in-10-oameni-17537276|title=Viitorul - Astra 1-0. B\u0103lu\u0163\u0103 a marcat golul victoriei \u00een prelungiri! Hagi a fost trimis \u00een tribune dup\u0103 ce s-a contrat cu staff-ul advers, giurgiuvenii au evoluat mai bine de o repriz\u0103 \u00een 10 oameni|trans-title=Viitorul - Astra 1\u20130. B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 scored the winner in the injury-time! Hagi was sent out after a conflict with the opposing staff, the Giurgiu men played more than half of the game with 10 footballers|publisher=[[ProSport]]|language=Romanian|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Brighton & Hove Albion===\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 agreed to a three-and-a-half-year contract with English club [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] on 31 January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-romania-international/|title=ALBION SIGN ROMANIA INTERNATIONAL|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made the bench for the first time for the ''Seagulls'' in a 2\u20131 away win over [[Bristol Rovers F.C.|Bristol Rovers]] in the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] on 27 August 2019 and was named on the bench in a [[Premier League]] fixture for the first time in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] on 14 September. He remained an unused substitute in both fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49402996 |title=Bristol Rovers v Brighton & Hove Albion - BBC Sport |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 August 2019 |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49617984|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-1 Burnley: Jeff Hendrick scores in stoppage time to earn visitors a point - BBC Sport|publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 September 2019|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref> B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 made his debut for the Sussex club in the [[2019\u201320 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]] playing the whole match in the 3\u20131 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 25 September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49736853|title=Brighton & Hove Albion 1-3 Aston Villa: Conor Hourihane scores win - BBC Sport |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 September 2019|accessdate=26 September 2019}}</ref> \n\n====Viitorul Constan\u021ba (loan)====\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 was immediately loaned back to Viitorul Constan\u021ba for the remainder of the [[2018\u201319 Liga I|campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brightonandhovealbion.com/news/2019/january/albion-sign-romania-international/|title=ALBION SIGN ROMANIA INTERNATIONAL|publisher=Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|date=31 January 2019|accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> Press reported the transfer fee at [[Euro|\u20ac]]3 million, which made him the club's most expensive sale at the time, tied with [[Florinel Coman]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bzi.ro/tudor-baluta-a-semnat-gica-hagi-si-a-egalat-recordul-ce-salariu-va-avea-mijlocasul-in-premier-league-681705|title=Tudor Baluta a semnat! Gica Hagi si-a egalat recordul! Ce salariu va avea mijlocasul, \u00een Premier League|trans-title=Tudor B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 has signed! Gic\u0103 Hagi equaled his record! What salary the midfielder will have in the Premier League|publisher=BZI|language=Romanian|date=30 August 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019|quote=Thus, Hagi equaled his record for the most expensive transfer in the history of the club. For Florinel Coman, Gigi Becali had also paid a total of 3 million euros.}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 May, he was a starter and played the full match in the [[Cupa Rom\u00e2niei]] final 2\u20131 success against Astra Giurgiu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziare.com/viitorul/stiri-viitorul/viitorul-lui-hagi-castiga-cupa-romaniei-dupa-o-finala-complicata-cu-astra-1562953|title=Viitorul lui Hagi castiga Cupa Romaniei dupa o finala complicata cu Astra|trans-title=Hagi's Viitorul wins the Romanian Cup after a difficult final with Astra|publisher=Ziare|language=Romanian|date=25 May 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 earned his first senior [[Cap (sports)|cap]] for [[Romania national football team|Romania]] on 31 May 2018, entering as a 71st-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for former Viitorul Constan\u021ba teammate [[Drago\u0219 Nedelcu]] in a 3\u20132 [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] victory against [[Chile national football team|Chile]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digisport.ro/fotbal/echipa-nationala/romania-chile-1700-tricolorii-in-linie-dreapta-inainte-de-liga-natiunilor-456136|title=Rom\u00e2nia - Chile 3-2. Rezerva Budescu a adus victoria tricolorilor. Sud-americanii au jucat o or\u0103 \u00een 10|trans-title=Romania - Chile 3\u20132. Substitute Budescu brought victory for \"the Tricolours\". The South Americans played for an hour in ten men|publisher=Digi Sport|language=Romanian|date=31 May 2018|accessdate=21 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite not playing in the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|qualification phase]], he was selected in [[Romania national under-21 football team|Romania]]'s squad for the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] in [[Italy]]. B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 scored on his debut against [[Croatia national under-21 football team|Croatia]] on 19 June that year, which ended in a 4\u20131 win for his side.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2019/matches/round=2000799/match=2025986/|title=Romania 4\u20131 Croatia|publisher=UEFA.com|date=18 June 2019|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> He recorded three more games as ''Tricolorii mici'' were eliminated by [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification#Semi-finals|semi-finals]], following a 2\u20134 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2019/matches/round=2000800/match=2027440/index.html|title=Germany 4\u20132 Romania|publisher=UEFA.com|date=27 June 2019|accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nB\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 is deployed primarily as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], but started out as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].<ref name=\"debut\"/> He has been likened to former Romanian international and [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] captain [[Gheorghe Popescu]], also a native of [[Dolj County]], who in his turn described B\u0103lu\u021b\u0103 as an \"intelligent player\" with \"exceptional qualities\".<ref name=\"gica_popescu\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|1 October 2019}}<ref>{{soccerway|tudor-cristian-blu/408625}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|Domestic Cup\n!colspan=2|League Cup\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[FC Viitorul Constan\u021ba|Viitorul Constan\u021ba]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Liga I|2015\u201316]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Liga I]]\n|2||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||1||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Liga I|2016\u201317]]\n|0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||0||0||0||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Liga I|2017\u201318]]\n|24||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||1||0||26||0\n|-\